title: DeepSeek, China, OpenAI, NVIDIA, xAI, TSMC, Stargate, and AI Megaclusters | Lex Fridman Podcast #459

metadata.summary: In this episode, Lex Fridman hosts Dylan Patel and Nathan Lambert to discuss the cutting edge of AI. They delve into DeepSeek's models, comparing them to OpenAI's, and explore the implications of open-source AI. The conversation covers China's AI advancements, export controls, and the potential for a new cold war. They also discuss the significance of TSMC, the best GPUs for AI, and the future of AI megaclusters. The discussion touches on espionage, censorship, and the role of reinforcement learning. The episode concludes with a look at the race to AGI, AI agents, and the future of AI.

topClaims.text: Deep Seek's models will be remembered as pivotal events in tech history due to their significant geopolitical implications.
Export controls will significantly reduce China's ability to run advanced AI models.
China's military has completely leapfrogged the US in drone capabilities.
China's industrial capacity far exceeds the United States, guaranteeing its long-term supremacy in AI and technology unless immediate action is taken.
The United States' leadership in AI will cause significant disadvantages for the Chinese people.

topQuotes.text: Deep Seek R1 shows the full Chain of Thought tokens, which I personally just love for these open-ended philosophical questions.
Humans instinctively convert selfish desires into cooperative systems by collectively pretending abstract rules, money, laws, and rights are real.
Superhuman persuasion will happen before superhuman intelligence.
The cost to serve multiplies by a ton.
The most peaceful time in human history has been when the US was the global hegemon.
